beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Shared with cbkschubert. Pours a golden brown color with a very small tan head. Very light spotty lacing. Smells like Brett. Thankfully for me it tastes better than it smells. Light caramel malts, tart cherries, and very light oakiness, with a tinge of vanilla.  Leaves a little tartness after the swallow, with a very slight alcohol warming affect.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours a clear deep reddish amber color, with a very small head that disappears quickly. No lacing. Aroma of tart fruit.  Flavor of tart cherries. A little too tart and bitter for me. Defenitely not my style of beer.

Pours a deep brown with a 1 1/2" mocha head. Almost no lacing. Aroma of mostly chocolate, roasty malts, coffee, and a very slight lingering coconut hue. Flavor is all chocolate, coffee, and roasted malts. I really cant detect the coconut in the flavor. Creamy, but a little dry. Over all a decent beer, but would like to taste the coconut.

Pours a light amber color with a small foamy white head that disappears quickly. Very spotty lacing. Aroma of sweet fruit. Flavor is of raspberries, a little tart, but not as tart as your typical lambic. Fairly easy to drink.

On tap at the new Liars Club. Pours a clear light amber color with a 1" quickly dissolving head. Nice lacing. Aroma of light hops, yeasty, spicey, and light banana. Flavors of about the same. Nice easy drinking.

Pours a dark brown with a 1"  mocha head that disappears quickly. Very spotty lacing. Aroma of roasty malts, licorice, dark esters, and chocolate. Flavors of molasses, roasty malts, light chocolate, licorice, and dark esters. Sweet and a little dry. Taste the alcohol a little, but definitely feel the warming sensation of the alcohol on the way down.

Pours a dark brown with a large foamy tan head. Nice lacing. Aroma of carroway seeds, with a light whiskey aroma. Flavors of coffee, roasted malts, whiskey, slight vanilla, and dark esters. 
Smooth beer. A little on the dry side. But overall a good tasting beer.

Rating #100 On tap at the new  Liars Club. Pours a deep clear brown with a nice creamy lasting tan head. Nice lacing. Aromas of roasty malts, chocolate, coffee(mocha). Flavors of the same. Very smooth and creamy beer. Of all the SD Brewing Co. beers Ive had,  this is  by far the best.

Pours a clear brown with a 1/4" off white head that disappears really quickly. Very spotty lacing. Aromas of coffee, chocolate, and very light malts. Flavors of roasted malts, slight coffee, and chocolate. Very thin body beer.
Pours a slightly hazy deep amber color with a small white head. Spotty lacing. Light toasted sweet malt. Flavor about the same. Sweet aftertaste. Worth a try but nothing special.

Pours a nice amber color with a very fine white head. On tap at Bobby Joes Irirsh Pub. Decent lacing. Aroma of light sweet malt, and sweetness. Flavor of sweetness, some caramel, and light malt. An okay beer, but not at the top of the list.

Pours a dark brown with a deep tan 1" head. Spotty lacing. Aromas of roasted malts, dark esters, light toffee, and light chocolate, slight coffee.  Flavors of the same. Nice smooth, creamy palate, with just a touch of dryness. Very good beer. The alcohol is hidden very well in this beer.
Pours a clear deep amber color with a big foamy cream colored head. Nice lacing. Aroma of woody malts, and light hops. Earthy tatste of hops and malts. Good easy drinking beer.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours a hazy golden color with a 1/2" foamy white head. Decent lacing. Aroma of citrus, hops, and earthy smells. Flavors of hops and citrus. Smells a lot hoppier than it tastes, good beer and not as bitter as most IPAs. These are typically not my style of beer, but I was rather impressed by this beer.
beer_name: Port Brewing High Tide  Fresh Hop IPA

review_blob: Pours a hazy amber, with a very slight pinkish color to it. Very light pink foamy head that disappears rather quickly.  Faint spotty lacing. Aroma of cough drop cherries. Flavor of cherry syrup. Not as tart as most lambics. Sweet easy drinking beer, but only one a night will do.

Pours a dark brown with a 1/2" tan head. Spotty lacing. Light spice, woody, and light chocolate aromas. Flavors of roasted malts, very light hops, light spice, and chocolate. Smooth, good beer, but you can taste the alcohol in it.
Batch # 002. Pours a slightly hazy deep amber color with a 1/2" white head. Very spotty lacing. Aromas of light malts and light esters. A little yeasty. Flavors of the same. Good beer.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Batch #35. Pours a cloudy amber color with little to no head. Some carbonation a little fizzy. Aroma of malts and apple cider, with a touch of honey. Flavors of the same. Pretty sweet beer.

Pours a clear amber color with a 1" cream colored head, that dissapears quickly. Decent lacing. Aromas of light sweet malts, caramel, toffee, and very light spices. Flavors of the same. Nice easy drinking light body beer.

Pours a slightly hazy amber color with very thin white head. No real lacing. Aroma of toffee, vanilla, caramel, and sweet malts. Flavors of about the same with the oakiness to it also. Hides the alcohol well in the taste, but you can definitely feel it.

Pours a black/brown color with a 1" light brown head. Very spotty lacing. Aroma of expresso/ coffee, light chocolate, roasty malts, and oak. Flavors of oak, coffee, very slight vanilla, and light chocolate. Smooth on the tounge,  a little bitter, but no lingering aftertaste. Wonder what would happen if I drank this for breakfast instead of the morning coffee.

Pours a deep dark brown with a 1/2" mocha head, that disapates quickly.  Spotty lacing. Aroma of chocolate and then some more chocolate. Flavor of chocolate. Smooth beer, alcohol is not apparent in the flavor, but it is felt going down. Very good dessert beer.

Pours a dark brown with a 1/2" tan head. Spotty lacing. Aromas of roasty malts, faint oak, and slight vanilla. Flavors of roasty malts, light vanilla, faint oak hues. A little bitter with a dry aftertaste.

2006 bottle. Pours a dark brown with almost no head. Aroma of roasted sweet malts and light alcohol scent. Flavor of molasses and sweet roasted malts, but no alcohol in the flavor. Did a side by side with an 02 that tasted like teriyaki sauce. Way past its prime.

Growler shared by cbkschubert. Pours a slightly hazy amber color with a 1/2" off white head. Spotty lacing.  Aroma of light malts, light hops, and earthy dirt. Flavor of sweet malt and earthiness. Overall an easy drinking beer with no lingering aftertastes.

Growler from Bockyhoresy. Pours a clear deep amber color with a small tan head. Light lacing. Aroma of sweet malt and caramel. Flavors of sweet malts and caramel. Smooth beer that hides alcohol very well.

Pours an amber color with and off white thin head. Nice lacing. Aroma of citrus, floral, hoppy notes. Flavor of citrus and hops. Not as hoppy as I expected. No bitter lingering aftertaste. Overall worth a try.

Pours a deep brown with a fine tan head. Very little lacing. Aroma of coffee and dark chocolate, with roasted malts. Flavors of basically the same. A little bitter. A decent somewhat smooth beer, but not as smooth as most oatmeal stouts.

Can, drank while in Minneapolis. Pours a light golden color with a thin white head. Worse than your average beer. Almost no aroma. Flavor is very bland and skunky.  Too used to good beer. Cant drink the low brau stuff any more.

On tap at Napa Valley Grille, Mall of America. Pours a dark brown almost black with a creamy tan head. Decent lacing. Aromas of espresso and dark chocolate. Flavors of roasted malts, espresso, and dark bitter chocolate. Dry and bitter, but better than Guinness.

Pours a clear deep golden color with a little white head. Spotty lacing. Aroma has citrus notes, piney hops, and light caramel. Tastes of the piney hops, citrus notes, and the light sweetness of caramel malts.  No lingering aftertaste.

Pours a slightly hazy deep golden color with a 1 off white head. Spotty lacing. 
Aroma of biscuity malt, and light hops. Flavor of a little stronger hops, with lighter malt hues. A little bitter, but over all a pretty good beer. No linger bitter aftertaste.

Pours a slightly hazy golden color with a big foamy white head.  Decent lacing. Aroma of light hops, light citrus, and  a little spice. Slight taste of honey and spice. Light body, easy drinking beer. Taste the honey on the palate afterwards.

Pours a clear mahogany color, with a 1/4"  bubbly off white head. Aroma of tart fruit. Almost a wine  taste, flavor of cherries. A little alcohol feeling going down. Shared by cbkschubert. No lingering aftertaste.  Tartness on the palate.

On tap at BJs in Tucson. Pours a clear amber color with almost no head. What was present was off white. Spotty lacing. Aroma of light sweet malt and not much else. Flavors of light sweet malt and very light caramel. Thats all I have to say about that beer.

Pours a clear brownish amber color with a 1/2" cream colored head that disapates very quickly. Almost no lacing. Aroma of all-spice and cloves. Tastes like spices. Light body. Okay beer, but wont rush out for another one.

Pours a dark golden color, not much head. Has decent lacing. Hops,  light esters, and citrus. Hoppy flavor with ligh citrus notes. Slightly bitter, but no lingering aftertaste. I dont usually like IPAs, but this is a good one.
Pours a pinkish color with a very small light pink head. Tastes like most of their other fruit beers. Fruity and sweet. Drinkable, but not overly impressed. Notes from last summer.
Pours a clear golden with no head. Aroma of sweetness and  light malt. Not detecting too much strawberry. Fruity, sweet flavor. Has a little funky aftertaste.

Pours a deep brown almost black, with a 1" foamy mocha head. Spotty lacing. Aromas of chocolate, coffee, vanilla, roasty malt, and dark esters. Flavors of coffee, light chocolate, roasty malts, very light vanilla, and some dark esters. Lighter body than most stouts, with a dry palate feel. You can feel the alcohol going down. Good beer.

Pours a ruby red grapefruit color from the 25cl can, with a very small light pink head that disapates quickly. Very spotty lacing. Aroma of light fruit, and light malt. Raspberry flavor. Very carbonated with no lingering aftertaste. The best thing about it is, I can ride around as a passanger, and the cops would think I was drinking an energy drink.

Pours a hazy golden color, with a 1/2" white head that disappears quickly. Spotty lacing. Aroma of light wheat and citrus. Citrus flavor with light yeast. Very light beer, easy to drink. This is the one you drink all night, and can still walk.
Pours a golden brown with almost no head, light lacing. Aroma of sweet roasted malts, caramel, and oak. Flavor is sweet caramel. Smooth with a little alcohol burn going down.

Shared with cbkschubert. Pors a dark hazy golden color with a off white head, that dissapears quickly. Spotty lacing. Aroma of light cherries, oak, and light esters. Flavor of ligh cherries, very tart beer. Not my style of beer, but worth a try.

Pours a hazy golden color, with a cream colored frothy head. Light lacing. Aroma of light esters, malts, and light yeast. Flavors of citrus, light esters, and light yeast. Light body, easy drinking beer.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours a dark brown, with almost no head and spotty  lacing. Aromas of oak, roasted malts, caramel, some dark esters, and very light vanilla. A slight alcohol smell also comes through. Flavors of roasted malts, caramel, light molasses, and hints of vanilla. A little bitter, but over all sweet and smooth. Feeling of alcohol warmness on the way down.

On tap at 1702. Pours a clear amber color with almost no head. Light lacing. Aromas of sweet malts, and light hops. Smooth beer, but from my understanding its not as hopped up as it is when first released. Some light esters in the flavor, sweet malts, and some hops.

Pours a deep burgandy rose color, with a fine light pink head. Aroma is definitely cherries, almost like  a cherry cough drop. Tastes of sweet and tart cherries. Good beer, but only one a night for me.

Pours a deep brown, with a frothy tan head. Spotty lacing. Aroma of roasted malt, has a metallic smell to it also. Flavor of toasted malt, with a very light chocolate flavor at the end. Medium body beer, thats okay, but nothing to write home about.
